<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-321-396  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 321 396.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  May 29 1989 v3 n22 p24(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ada: ten years after. (machine-independent programming language)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fluty, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The year 1989 marks the tenth anniversary of the creation of Ada,the all-purpose, machine-independent programming language createdfor the military's mission-critical systems.andP;  The language hasbeen used in many different military and civilian agency systems.andO;Users are now making improvements to the language so that it canbe linked to other software tools and languages.andP;  Ada companiesare also developing compilers that address the 32-bitmicroprocessor market and use reduced-instruction-set computerpower to speed up code generation.andP;  Ada products today seemsimilar to CASE tools, and companies are merging the two productsas the demand for software engineering tools grows.andP;  One observersees Ada being used by 80 to 90 percent of the users at theDepartment of Defense by 1993 or 1994.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ADAMilitaryProgramming LanguagesEnhancementsConnectivityUpgrading.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>